  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1989974682" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1989974682" />
    <a title="Jacob van Berkel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8350311-jacob-van-berkel"><img alt="Jacob van Berkel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1488283144p2/8350311.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1989974682?book_show_action=true">Jul 30, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jacob van Berkel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jacob van Berkel" href="/user/show/8350311-jacob-van-berkel">Jacob van Berkel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">people interested in reading good novels</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Jacob by: </span>
      John W. Dower
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8350311-jacob-van-berkel?shelf=broad-century-of-humiliation">broad-century-of-humiliation</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1989974682" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5855981815737475581">For Private Tamura, the narrator and protagonist of this novel, the story starts with being yelled at and slapped in the face by his commanding officer. He is also deadly sick with consumption, stuck on an island far away from home, part of an army that has already lost the war, surrounded by hostile local guerillas that intend to do unspeakable things to him and his comrades, and is under constant attack from an enemy air force that is superior in both resources and firepower. What makes all th</span>
  <span id="freeText5855981815737475581" style="display:none">For Private Tamura, the narrator and protagonist of this novel, the story starts with being yelled at and slapped in the face by his commanding officer. He is also deadly sick with consumption, stuck on an island far away from home, part of an army that has already lost the war, surrounded by hostile local guerillas that intend to do unspeakable things to him and his comrades, and is under constant attack from an enemy air force that is superior in both resources and firepower. What makes all this worse is that his army is also starving, and very, very desperate for food. <br /><br />This is last fact is why his commanding officer is yelling at and slapping Tamura: if he's too sick to help forage for food, he needs to not be here at all. Which is why, at the very outset of the story, Private Tamura, besides all these other problems, is ordered to get rid of himself. To go to the Japanese military hospital to be treated there, and if they won't take him (which they won't, because they only take patients who bring their own food) kill himself. <br /><br />It all goes downhill from there.<br /><br />This is truly a great novel. Imagine <i>Lord of the Flies</i> meets <i>Grizzly Man</i>, or maybe <i>Heart of Darkness</i> meets <i>Crime and Punishment</i>. In either or any other case, this novel is not only as psychologically convincing as any Dostoevsky, but also - and of course exactly because of that - truly and rarely dark. <br /><br />On top of that, as extreme as both his circumstances and behaviors are, Private Tamura is an instantly relatable and recognizably human character. Which makes the novel even more impressive, as soldiers of the the Imperial Japanese Army are known for a lot of things in the West, but not their relatability. <br /> <br />Tamura's idiosyncratic attitude to his hopelessness is what does the trick. I'm dead anyway, and as I still have my hand grenade, I can even die whenever I like, so I don't have to suffer ... and will just enjoy my final moments as I please. His liberation reminds us of Tyler Durden: <i>"It's only after we've lost everything, that we're free to do anything."</i><br /><br />Tamura's reaction when he soon sees his comrades cut into pieces by the machine guns of an American airplane drives home the extent of his Durdenesque liberation, or loss of humanity if you will - he bursts into laughing, it's funny to him. <br /><br />As inhuman as this reaction seems, it's exactly this lost humanity what makes Tamura so human. <i>Of course</i> he would have given up on both himself and his comrades. <i>Of course</i> it's funny that his fellow soldiers are now dead, because not mattered anymore anyway, and now they even matter less. What sort of a dumb freak would cling to hope if there isn't any? Characters in bad movies do that, or bad novels perhaps ... but not a real human being, like Private Tamura. <br /><br />This extreme but convincing humanity is shared by other characters. Most notably two of Tamura's fellow soldiers, a young private and a middle-aged officer, who have taken up the habit of calling each other 'son' and 'dad'. Their bickering over food and tobacco in the early part of the novel feels very realistic,* as does their later descent into madness. <br /><br />If you get the chance you should definitely read it. <br />________<br />* This is the part where I noticed how much I liked Ivan Morris's translation, as parts like these can be really messed up if a translator is not a good writer in addition to being a good linguist. No matter how skillfully and natural Ōoka wrote these dialogues down, in translation they are only allowed to feel natural if the language of the translator feels natural. </span>
  <a data-text-id="5855981815737475581" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


