  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2791457471" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2791457471" />
    <a title="Christina" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/26102665-christina"><img alt="Christina" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1385703847p2/26102665.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2791457471?book_show_action=true">Jul 27, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christina" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christina" href="/user/show/26102665-christina">Christina</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26102665-christina?shelf=good-but-wont-reread">good-but-wont-reread</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2791457471" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9891287140917766211">Ooka does a wonderful job taking readers through stages of despair and bringing war experiences to the hearts and minds of people like me, who have only known peace. What I absolutely loved about this novel though is its Eastern perspective. There is no &quot;appeal&quot; like the typical &quot;enemy-soldier-is-secretly-good-guy-among-devils&quot; story, there is no &quot;patriotism, pride, and honor&quot; in typical American war stories, there is no &quot;I am the one sane person who knows fear in war&quot; like <i>The Red Badge of Cour</i></span>
  <span id="freeText9891287140917766211" style="display:none">Ooka does a wonderful job taking readers through stages of despair and bringing war experiences to the hearts and minds of people like me, who have only known peace. What I absolutely loved about this novel though is its Eastern perspective. There is no "appeal" like the typical "enemy-soldier-is-secretly-good-guy-among-devils" story, there is no "patriotism, pride, and honor" in typical American war stories, there is no "I am the one sane person who knows fear in war" like <i>The Red Badge of Courage</i>. In wholeness, <i>Fires on the Plain</i> focuses on only the humanity and not the morality or righteousness. <br /><br />In a similar vein to <i>Girl, Interrupted</i> or <i>The Bell Jar</i>, Ooka narrates in a direct, pragmatic style. While the scenes and actions become abhorrent, they somehow seem so normal in the description. I know the narrator is going crazy with loneliness, despair, internal conflict, hunger, desperation, etc., but I don't really <i>know</i>.<br /><br />Additionally, Ooka paces the story phenomenally. While the narrator suffers from loneliness and lost aimlessness, the story seems slow, as if to drag, with too much introspection. And I mean "too much" as in "this is exactly how I could imagine wasting my day if I was in a similar situation." The action picks up and the pace of the story quickens when the narrator has a goal, becoming somehow introspective but laced with less introspection. There are certainly scenes of war - scenes of killing, of understanding hatred from one side to another, of fearing an enemy, but they're abstracted away from the underlying politics. I can't describe it, but it becomes about the human interactions and how emotions and perceptions of the moment affect actions, not about "I-got-thrown-here-and-I'm-angry-at-the-political-schemers-who-forced-me-to-such-actions."<br /><br />I loved the storytelling, and I think the message came across very clearly. It's just a personal thing why I would never reread this book (can be too gory in some descriptions, and I'm never really captivated by war stories), but it's a book I will certainly recommend, suggest, and hope to pass on to someone who will take as much away from it as I did.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9891287140917766211" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


